    <header>SymPage Help</header>

    <div class="article-name">How to Use SymPage</div>
    <article>
        <p>
            Welcome to the help section for the <strong>SymPage Symbolic Calculator</strong>. This page allows you to perform two primary operations: simplifying complex mathematical expressions and solving equations.
        </p>
        <p>
            The interface is composed of a toolbar and two text panes:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Input Pane:</strong> This is where you type the expression you want to work with. You can also load pre-made examples using the dropdown menus in the toolbar.</li>
            <li><strong>Output Pane:</strong> This read-only pane displays the result of your calculation after you click an operation button.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            The toolbar contains the main controls:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong style="vertical-align: middle;">Simplify:</strong> The main workhorse. It evaluates and simplifies the expression in the Input pane. This is also used to perform calculus operations.</li>
            <li><strong style="vertical-align: middle;">Solve:</strong> Solves an equation for a specific variable.</li>
            <li><strong style="vertical-align: middle;">Examples Dropdowns:</strong> Use these to select a sample expression. The selected example will automatically appear in the Input pane, ready for you to use.</li>
        </ul>
    </article>

    <hr />

    <div class="article-name">Simplify Operation</div>
    <article>
        <p>
            The <strong>Simplify</strong> button takes the expression from the Input pane and applies a comprehensive set of algebraic and calculus rules to reduce it to its simplest form.
        </p>

        <h3>Algebraic Simplification</h3>
        <p>This includes combining like terms, evaluating numerical expressions, and applying identity rules.</p>
        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <pre><code>(x + y) * 1</code></pre>
        <p>Clicking <strong>Simplify</strong> will produce:</p>
        <pre><code>x + y</code></pre>

        <hr class="inner-hr" />

        <h3>Calculus & Vector Operations</h3>
        <p>
            To perform calculus or vector operations like differentiation, integration, or gradient, you must write them using function syntax. After writing the function call in the Input pane, click the <strong>Simplify</strong> button to get the result.
        </p>
        <p><strong>Example (Differentiation):</strong></p>
        <p>To find the derivative of <code>x**2</code>, you would enter the following and click <strong>Simplify</strong>:</p>
        <pre><code>Derivative(x**2, x)</code></pre>
        <p><strong>Result:</strong></p>
        <pre><code>2 * x</code></pre>

        <p><strong>Example (Gradient):</strong></p>
        <p>To find the gradient of the scalar field <code>x*y</code>, you would enter:</p>
        <pre><code>Grad(x*y, Vector(x, y))</code></pre>
        <p><strong>Result:</strong></p>
        <pre><code>Vector(y, x)</code></pre>
    </article>

    <hr />

    <div class="article-name">Solve Operation</div>
    <article>
        <p>
            The <strong>Solve</strong> button is used to isolate a variable within an equation.
        </p>
        <p>
            The input must be a <strong>single line</strong> containing the equation, followed by a comma, and then the variable you wish to solve for.
        </p>
        <p><strong>Required Format:</strong> <code>equation, variable</code></p>
        <p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
        <p>To solve the equation <code>a*x + b = c</code> for the variable <code>x</code>, you would enter:</p>
        <pre><code>a*x + b = c, x</code></pre>
        <p>Clicking <strong>Solve</strong> will produce:</p>
        <pre><code>x = (c - b) / a</code></pre>
    </article>

    <hr />

    <div class="article-name">Syntax and Functions</div>
    <article>
        <h3>Operators</h3>
        <p>Sym uses the following operators, listed in order of precedence (lowest to highest):</p>
        <table class="help-table">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Operator</th>
                    <th>Description</th>
                    <th>Example</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                <tr>
                    <td><code>=</code></td>
                    <td>Equality (for defining equations)</td>
                    <td><code>2 * x = 10</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><code>+</code></td>
                    <td>Addition</td>
                    <td><code>x + y</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><code>-</code></td>
                    <td>Subtraction / Unary Minus</td>
                    <td><code>5 - z</code> or <code>-x</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><code>*</code></td>
                    <td>Multiplication</td>
                    <td><code>3 * (x + 1)</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><code>/</code></td>
                    <td>Division</td>
                    <td><code>y / 2</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td><code>**</code></td>
                    <td>Power / Exponentiation</td>
                    <td><code>x**2</code></td>
                </tr>
            </tbody>
        </table>

        <h3>Supported Functions</h3>
        <p>The following functions can be used in your expressions:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Calculus:</strong> <code>Derivative(expr, var)</code>, <code>Integral(expr, var)</code></li>
            <li><strong>Vector Calculus:</strong> <code>Grad(scalar_expr, vec_var)</code>, <code>Div(vec_expr, vec_var)</code>, <code>Curl(vec_expr, vec_var)</code></li>
            <li><strong>Data Structures:</strong> <code>Vector(c1, c2, ...)</code></li>
            <li><strong>Standard Math:</strong> <code>sin(x)</code>, <code>cos(x)</code>, <code>tan(x)</code>, <code>exp(x)</code>, <code>log(x)</code>, <code>sqrt(x)</code></li>
        </ul>
    </article>

